The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 Chennai: The Indian junior volleyball team is just a step away from defending their title at the 24th Memorial Ferruccio Cornacchia international men?s championship.

 In a repeat of last year?s final, India will face Hungary in the championship match at San Giorgio de Porcia, Italy. After having topped group B, India defeated Algeria 25-18, 25-23, 25-22 in the quarter finals and got past Germany in the semi-finals on Sunday.

 After losing the first set 23-25, India won the second on extra points (30-28) and never looked back, taking the next two 25-14 and 25-19.

 Chikmagalur: Wild card entrants Vishal Uppal and Mustafa Ghouse crashed out of the $ 25,000 Coffee Cup ATP challenger which began here on Monday.

 In first-round matches, Ghouse went down to third seed Yen-Hsun Lu of Taipei 3-6, 2-6, while Uppal lost to second seed Danai Udomchoke of Thailand 4-6, 2-6.

 Meanwhile, Philip King of the US, the lucky loser in the qualifying round who gained entry into the main draw after Harsh Mankad pulled out because of knee injury, advanced to the second round. The American beat German Sebastian Rieschick 6-3, 6-2. 

 London: Jose Maria Olazabal has confirmed his participation in next month?s BMW Championship at Wentworth, the event he rates the most important outside the four Majors.

 The 40-year-old Spaniard picked up the title in 1994 and has never missed the cut in the tournament formerly known as the PGA Championship.

 ?I recall winning the PGA five weeks after my first US Masters victory,? Olazabal said in a news release on Monday. ?That was the icing on the cake in 1994 because if I had to choose any title outside the Majors, this is the one to win.? 

 New Delhi: Melbourne Commonwealth Games bronze medallist Manavjit Singh Sandhu shot a score of 142 to win the trap gold medal at the fourth Sardar Sajjan Singh Sethi Memorial Masters shooting meet here on Monday.

 Manavjit aggregated 119 points in qualifications and fired a final round of 23.

 Anwer Sultan claimed the silver with 137 points while Mansher Singh bagged bronze with 135.

 Amit Sanghi scored 128 points to top the skeet field which saw a close finish. The Andhra shooter hit 111 and 17 in the qualifying and the final rounds, respectively, to pick the gold medal.

 Baba Bedi was just a point adrift at 127 to take the silver while Amardeep Rai?s bronze came with 126points.

 Beijing: China?s Zhang Xiyan claimed the nation?s first professional boxing title at the weekend when she outpointed America?s Alicia Ashley to lift the WBC women?s lightweight crown. Zhang?s 10-round unanimous points victory on Saturday delighted home fans in China?s southwest city of Chengdu and had the country?s boxing officials talking up a new era for the sport. 

 Zhang turned professional only three months ago. 

 Boston: Kenyan Rita Jeptoo won the Boston Marathon on Monday, overtaking last years New York City Marathon winner Jelena Prokopcuka of Latvia and Reiko Tosa of Japan who dominated the first half in the womens field.

 Jeptoo, 25, won the 110th edition of the worlds oldest marathon in an unofficial time of 2:23:38 seconds. The time fell short of the womens course record of 2:20:43 set by Margaret Okayo of Kenya in 2002. It was Jeptoos first marathon in the US. 

